+3. ~~**What is a crisp, agent-legible definition of "good stopping point"?**~~
+   **ANSWERED (2026-07-18, xray — full write-up in `DIRECTION.md` §Q3).** A crisp
+   definition exists, framed as **reconstruction cost from durable substrate**: a
+   stopping point is GOOD when the *delta* between what's in the agent's context and
+   what's already durably recorded (disk / beads / queue / a bounded handoff) is
+   small enough to serialize losslessly. Agent self-test (4-item checklist): (i)
+   between discrete units, not mid-edit/mid-plan/mid-tool-sequence; (ii) all in-flight
+   work committed to durable substrate or trivially re-derivable; (iii) no unanswered
+   operator question / half-composed reply being held; (iv) next session, reading only
+   handoff + substrate, resumes with no redo and no lost decision. All four yes → good.
+   **Key design implication:** this test is **agent-legible, NOT keeper-legible** — the
+   keeper cannot read context to detect it, so the *agent* must own the self-assessment
+   and the keeper can only **bound** it with a deadline (seek a good point within a
+   window; FORCE-ACT cuts if none arrives). This is exactly why the agent-initiated
+   deferred-restart path (I3 / `restart-now`) is the right vehicle, not keeper-side
+   detection. CrispIdle (turn boundary, keeper-legible) is a coarse proxy for this
+   (task boundary, agent-legible); the gap between the two IS the "agents get confused"
+   ambiguity the operator observed.
